{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:46:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:46:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"74"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/74"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.63,0.13,0.19,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"74"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/74"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-09-26T01:35:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T10:55:07+10:30","updatedAction":"revised","acceptedAt":null,"editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 16:01:33"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"74"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41979"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75864"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman is brought to a General Practice clinic by her daughter who says she \u0022Just cannot look after her mother anymore\u0022. On further history, the daughter reveals that her mother had moved in with her after the death of her father nine months ago. She says her mother has been forgetful, often forgetting to turn off the stove when cooking and has wandered out of the house several times. She has also noticed her mother has become increasingly incontinent. She has a medical history of hypertension and gastro-oesophageal reflux. Her medications include amlodipine and esomeprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination demonstrates a gait that is broad-based and difficult to initiate. The rest of the neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ischaemic cerebellar stroke","Normal pressure hydrocephalus","Parkinson\u0027s disease","Early stage Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Multiple sclerosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe triad of\u00a0gait dysfunction,\u00a0cognitive impairment\u00a0and incontinence in an older patient\u00a0is the characteristic presentation of\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Enormal pressure hydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u00a0This condition may be idiopathic, or secondary to conditions such as subarachnoid haemorrhage and meningitis. Ventriculomegaly is a feature that can be seen on imaging. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThough memory loss is a feature of early \u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer disease\u003C/strong\u003E, changes in gait are unlikely early in the course of disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson disease\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a narrow based, shuffling gate. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with variable neurological symptoms that may include motor dysfunction, cognitive impairment and bladder dysfunction; however, this is unlikely to present at this age (it is typically diagnosed in a patient\u2019s second to third decade of life), and is more likely to present with episodes of neurological dysfunction followed by full or partial resolution. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellar infarcts\u003C/strong\u003E may be associated with gait dysfunction. However, they are likely to present acutely with associated nausea, vomiting, vertigo, and dizziness, rather than incontinence and memory dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The triad of\u00a0gait dysfunction,\u00a0cognitive impairment\u00a0and incontinence in an older patient\u00a0is the characteristic presentation of\u00a0normal pressure hydrocephalus."],"references":["Oliveira L, Nitrini R, Roman G. Normal-pressure hydrocephalus: A critical review. Dement Neuropsychol. 2019;13(2):133-143. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6601311/","Honig L, Mayeux R. Natural history of Alzheimer\u2019s disease. Aging Clin Exp Res. 2001;13:171-182. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11442300/","Ghasemi N, Razavi S, Nikzad E. Multiple Sclerosis: Pathogenesis, Symptoms, Diagnoses and Cell-Based Therapy. 2017; 19(1):1-10. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28367411/","Wright J, Huang C, Strbian D, Sundararajan S. Diagnosis and Management of Acute Cerebellar Infarction. American Heart Association. 2014;45(4):56-58. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/STROKEAHA.114.004474"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"74"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T10:55:07+10:30","u